"{\n  \"text\": \"First question everybody asks about fermenting is what is the difference between fermenting and pickling? And they are fundamentally different, even though they seem like they have very similar results and they're both sour vegetables. The main difference is that vinegar is used in pickling and salt water is used in fermenting, and that's a fundamental difference because vinegar locks out bacteria of every type. Probiotic, beneficial, pathogenic, all the bacteria gets locked out. So anaerobic and aerobic bacteria both are removed in the pickling process. And the fermenting process is use salt water, which encourages beneficial anaerobic growth of bacteria. And what happens in turn in that is it locks out pathogenic bacteria that causes vegetables to rot and mold. Both of them are preservation methods. Both of them work fine for preserving preserving vegetables. But the big difference with fermenting is that it's so much healthier for you. Whenever you get this beneficial bacteria cultivated in the vegetable, it's like a pre-digestion for your food. It basically breaks down a lot of the food molecules the same way that your digestive tract will, because you digest anaerobically as well, which is uh without oxygen or it thrives in an environment without oxygen. And so basically, whenever you cultivate vegetables with this type of bacteria, you promote easy digestion, but you also teach your bacteria how to do a better job digesting your sugars and sarches. And that's because the probiotic bacteria found in fermented foods teaches your bacteria how to do a better job. It's a fascinating process, and very few things that actually help digestion do go that far to teach your bacteria how to do a better job. Anyway, I'll get back into this in my other videos, and uh I hope you have a great day. Thanks.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" First question everybody asks about fermenting is what is the difference between fermenting and pickling?